VALUES
(42, 11, 44, 40, 23, 27, 28, 'hypocrites! for ye are as graves', 'Hypocrisy of Religious Leaders', 'Both passages emphasize the hypocrisy of the scribes and Pharisees, comparing them to graves or sepulchres that appear outwardly beautiful but are inwardly corrupt. This connection highlights the theme of outward appearances versus inner reality.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 44, 19, 5, 9, 9, NULL, 'Connection of Hypocrisy and Deceit', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of hypocrisy and deceit. Luke 11:44 describes the scribes and Pharisees as ''graves which appear not,'' while Psalms 5:9 refers to the throat as ''an open sepulchre,'' highlighting the hidden wickedness within.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 44, 4, 19, 16, 16, 'graves which appear not', 'Connection of Graves and Purity', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of graves and their associated uncleanness. Luke 11:44 warns of the hidden graves, while Numbers 19:16 outlines the impurity that comes from contact with a grave.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 44, 44, 23, 3, 3, NULL, 'Hypocrisy and Judgment', 'This connection highlights the theme of hypocrisy in both passages. In Luke, the scribes and Pharisees are likened to hidden graves, while in Acts, Paul calls out a judge as a ''whited wall,'' suggesting a facade of righteousness.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 44, 28, 9, 8, 8, NULL, 'Hypocrisy and Spiritual Blindness', 'This connection highlights the theme of spiritual blindness and hypocrisy. Both passages emphasize the danger of being unaware of one''s own spiritual state, as seen in the metaphor of graves in Luke and the snare in Hosea.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 45, 24, 6, 10, 10, 'reproach', 'Reproach of the Word', 'This connection highlights the theme of reproach found in both passages. In Luke, the lawyer acknowledges that Jesus'' words are a reproach to them, while Jeremiah describes the word of the Lord as a reproach to the people who do not listen.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 45, 40, 22, 35, 35, 'lawyer', 'Lawyers Questioning Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the role of lawyers questioning Jesus. In Luke, a lawyer responds to Jesus, while in Matthew, a lawyer asks Jesus a question. This connection highlights the interaction between Jesus and legal experts.', 'parallel', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 45, 43, 9, 40, 40, 'thus saying thou reproachest us also', 'Reproach and Blindness Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of self-awareness and accountability among religious leaders. In both passages, the lawyers and Pharisees respond defensively to Jesus'' words, indicating a lack of recognition of their own spiritual blindness.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 45, 11, 22, 8, 8, 'thus saying thou reproachest us also', 'Reproach of False Prophets', 'This connection highlights the theme of reproach towards those who speak the truth. In both passages, the lawyers and the king express disdain for those who do not align with their desires, indicating a resistance to genuine prophetic voices.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 45, 24, 20, 8, 8, 'thou reproachest us also', 'Reproach and Derision Theme', 'This connection highlights the theme of reproach found in both passages. In Luke, the lawyer perceives Jesus'' words as a reproach, while Jeremiah expresses that the word of the Lord has become a reproach and derision to him.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 45, 30, 7, 10, 13, 'thus saying thou reproachest us also', 'Reproach of Authority Figures', 'This connection highlights the theme of reproach directed at religious authorities. In both passages, figures of authority respond negatively to prophetic messages that challenge their power and status.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 45, 42, 11, 46, 46, 'thus saying thou reproachest us also', 'Reproach of Lawyers', 'This connection highlights the response of the lawyers to Jesus'' criticism. Both passages emphasize the burdens placed on others by the lawyers, indicating their hypocrisy in not sharing the load.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 46, 42, 11, 52, 52, 'burdens grievous to be borne', 'Burden and Knowledge Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the burdens imposed by lawyers on others. The first highlights how they do not help, while the second shows their failure to provide knowledge, hindering others.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 46, 23, 10, 1, 1, 'grievous to be borne', 'Burden of Unrighteous Decrees', 'Both passages emphasize the imposition of burdensome and unjust laws on others. Luke 11:46 speaks of lawyers loading men with grievous burdens, while Isaiah 10:1 condemns those who decree unrighteous decrees. This connection highlights a shared theme of oppressive leadership.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 46, 40, 23, 2, 4, NULL, 'Burden of the Law', 'Both passages emphasize the heavy burdens placed on people by religious leaders, highlighting their hypocrisy in not sharing the load. The phrase ''heavy burdens and grievous to be borne'' appears in both texts, reinforcing this theme.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 46, 42, 11, 45, 45, NULL, 'Reproach of the Lawyers', 'This connection highlights the response of the lawyers to Jesus'' criticism. Both passages emphasize the burden placed on others and the lawyers'' awareness of their own shortcomings.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 46, 48, 6, 13, 13, 'burdens grievous to be borne', 'Burden of the Law', 'This connection highlights the theme of imposing burdens. In Luke, the lawyers are criticized for laying heavy burdens on others without helping, while in Galatians, those who are circumcised are noted for not keeping the law themselves yet desire to impose it on others.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 46, 23, 58, 6, 6, NULL, 'Burden and Oppression Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of heavy burdens. Luke 11:46 criticizes those who impose such burdens, while Isaiah 58:6 calls for the undoing of heavy burdens and the liberation of the oppressed.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 47, 52, 2, 15, 15, NULL, 'Connection of Persecution of Prophets', 'Both passages emphasize the killing of prophets and the rejection of God''s messengers. Luke highlights the building of sepulchres for prophets while acknowledging their murder, and 1 Thessalonians directly states the killing of prophets and Jesus.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 47, 44, 7, 51, 51, 'your fathers killed them', 'Resistance to Prophetic Messages', 'Both passages emphasize the rejection of prophets by their ancestors and the continuation of this behavior in the present. This connection highlights a pattern of resistance to divine messages throughout generations.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 47, 40, 23, 29, 33, 'ye build the sepulchres of the prophets', 'Condemnation of Hypocrisy', 'Both passages emphasize the act of building sepulchres for the prophets while condemning the actions of their ancestors who killed them. This connection highlights the hypocrisy of claiming righteousness while being complicit in the sins of the past.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 48, 59, 5, 10, 10, 'ye allow the deeds of your fathers', 'Prophets and Their Suffering', 'Both passages emphasize the suffering of prophets. Luke highlights the actions of those who killed prophets, while James encourages patience in the face of affliction, reflecting the legacy of those prophets.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 48, 14, 36, 16, 16, 'ye allow the deeds of your fathers', 'Rejection of God''s Messengers', 'Both passages emphasize the rejection of God''s messengers. In Luke, the people acknowledge their ancestors'' actions against prophets, while in 2 Chronicles, the mocking and despising of God''s messengers leads to dire consequences.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 48, 40, 21, 35, 38, 'killed them', 'Connection of Rejection and Violence', 'This connection highlights the theme of rejecting and killing God''s messengers. Both passages emphasize the violent actions taken against those sent by God, culminating in the killing of the son in Matthew, paralleling the acknowledgment of past deeds in Luke.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 48, 40, 23, 31, 31, NULL, 'Witnessing the Actions of Ancestors', 'This connection highlights the theme of witnessing the actions of previous generations. Both passages emphasize that the current generation acknowledges their forebears'' role in killing the prophets.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 48, 44, 7, 51, 52, 'ye allow the deeds of your fathers', 'Resistance to Prophets', 'Both passages emphasize the actions of the fathers in persecuting prophets. Luke highlights the building of sepulchres for those killed, while Acts directly accuses the current generation of repeating their fathers'' actions. This connection highlights a theme of continuity in resistance to divine messengers.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 48, 58, 11, 35, 38, 'ye allow the deeds of your fathers', 'Persecution of the Righteous', 'This connection highlights the theme of persecution faced by the prophets and faithful individuals. Both passages emphasize the suffering endured by those who stand for truth, with Luke referencing the deeds of the fathers and Hebrews detailing the trials of the faithful.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 48, 6, 24, 22, 22, NULL, 'Witness and Accountability Theme', 'This connection highlights the theme of witness and accountability in both passages. Luke 11:48 discusses how the people bear witness to the deeds of their ancestors, while Joshua 24:22 emphasizes the people''s own witness to their choice to serve the Lord.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 49, 46, 1, 30, 30, 'wisdom of God', 'Connection of Wisdom and Prophets', 'This connection highlights the theme of wisdom in both passages. In Luke, the ''wisdom of God'' sends prophets, while in 1 Corinthians, Christ is described as ''made unto us wisdom.''', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 49, 51, 2, 3, 3, 'wisdom of God', 'Connection of Wisdom and Knowledge', 'This connection highlights the theme of wisdom in both passages. Luke 11:49 refers to the ''wisdom of God'' sending prophets, while Colossians 2:3 states that all treasures of wisdom and knowledge are found in Christ.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
